summary.seg: This manuscript is a Psalter in Greek, probably copied around the 1460s. The Psalms are followed by the Odes, the sequence of hymns excerpted from various Biblical books, also known as canticles, which in the Orthodox tradition constitute a separate book of the Bible. The first nine of these are the basis for the canons which are a central component of Orthodox hymnography. This manuscript contains this basic set and three of the remaining six hymns, arranged in their most usual order.

The manuscript has been identified from its distinctive script as the work of a copyist named Manuel, originally from Constantinople, who produced a number of other manuscripts and whose identity is known from his colophon on a New Testament manuscript (Leicester, The Record Office for Leicestershire, Leicester and Rutland, MS 6 D 32/1), addressed to George Neville, Archbishop of York (c. 1433-1476) Neville, George, 1433?-1476 and dated 1468. The likelihood that Manuel had settled in England is reinforced by evidence from other manuscripts that he collaborated with another known Constantinopolitan scribe, Ioannes Serbopoulos, who lived and worked in Reading, producing dated manuscripts between 1484 and 1500. Although he was able to find work as a copyist, it seems likely that Manuel had not been professionally trained as a scribe. His hand is not very elegant and somewhat unconventional, and his accentuation is erroneous, using acute accents wherever a grave accent should appear. He was perhaps a refugee from the Ottoman conquest who adopted a new trade after settling in the West, taking advantage of the potential market value of a basic level of Greek literacy in England, where such skills were rare.

Another indication that Manuel produced this manuscript in England is the presence of Latin annotations by a 15th-century hand, whose style suggests an English origin, who added occasional glosses of words and identified most of the Psalms by number and by the incipit of their Latin translation. These may well be the work of the manuscript's original patron, as they are absent from the first quire, whose text is in Manuel's hand but in slightly larger script than the rest. This suggests that this quire may have been a replacement produced to remedy damage to the original first quire, soon enough after the book's production for the original scribe to be commissioned to do the work, but after the Latin annotations had been added, and that those lost with the removal of the original quire were never replicated in the substitute.

The manuscript retains an early binding, which has been identified as the work of a London craftsman active from the 1450s until the 1480s, known from one of the decorative motifs he used as the "Scales Binder". This was one of the earliest English binders to produce bindings with their leather covers decorated with tooling. The design includes the name Bhale, probably that of the owner for whom the book was bound. Study of the different decorative tools employed by the binder at different times suggests that this binding was produced in the years around 1470 and must therefore have been done not long after the copying of the manuscript. However, if the current first quire is indeed a replacement, this may nonetheless be a rebinding. This would also be suggested by the presence of stains from leather turn-ins on f. [ii] but not on f. [i], suggesting that the present second endleaf was previously the first.

In the light of this, it is peculiar that the manuscript bears no less than four sets of quire or leaf signatures, which would normally suggest that it had been rebound on multiple occasions and its quires relabelled for the purpose. One of these signature sequences numbers the quires only, in Arabic numerals, while the other three also number the bifolios within each quire. Two of these leaf signature sequences use Latin letters for quires and Roman numerals for bifolios, one of which has been identified as the work of the Scales Binder. The other is written in Greek, apparently in Manuel's own hand. While the use of quire signatures was a normal feature of Greek manuscripts, leaf signatures were not usual in the Byzantine tradition. Manuel's adoption of this practice may be a further reflection of his residence in western Europe, and perhaps of his lack of formal scribal training, leaving him to learn aspects of his trade in the West rather than retaining habits acquired in Constantinople.

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), of medium thickness and quality, with a somewhat hairy texture. There are some holes and flaws originating in the process of production, occasionally in the written area, but the coloration is pale and consistent, with little trace of follicles.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers [i-iii] + 1-152 + [iv-v] in Arabic numerals, in pencil, recto, upper right.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 19 quires, all quaternia.
collation.signatures: There are early leaf signatures in Greek numerals, in brown ink, on the first folio of each bifolio, recto, lower right, probably original to the production of the manusript. On the first leaf of each quire only the quire number appears, on the rest both quire and leaf numbers on some quires, on others only leaf numbers. They survive on all quires (αʹ-ιθʹ), but a few have been partially lost to cropping or damage.

There is also a later sequence of leaf signatures in Latin letters and Arabic numerals, in brown ink, on the first folio of each bifolio, recto, lower right. Some have been wholly or partially lost to cropping or damage. These have been identified as the work of the Scales Binder (Barker, 'Scales Binder', p. 373).

A third sequence of leaf signatures appears, in Latin letters and Roman numerals, in red crayon, on the first folio of each bifolio, recto, lower right or lower centre. They survive on all quires, but some are severely faded.
There are also quire signatures in Arabic numerals, in brown ink, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower centre. Some have been wholly or partially lost to cropping.
collation.catchwords: There are catchwords on the last folio of each quire, verso, lower right, by the original copyist.

supportDesc.condition: A hole in f. 23 and a flaw in f. 22, formed in the process of production, were formerly repaired with stitching, since removed. A hole of similar origin at the edge of f. 152 has been repaired with a parchment patch. There is slight cockling and occasional creasing, and some areas of dirt.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 19 lines. 195 145
Verses often, but not always, begin with a new line. Text has often been added beneath the last full line of a page to complete a verse before the page transition

handNote.p: The main text was copied by Manuel of Constantinople (Hand A) (RGK I 115, II 147) in mixed minuscule script, slanting to the right, in brown ink, with modest variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is absent. There is decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all lengths of nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to breathings and nomina sacra strokes. Grave accents do not appear, acute accents being used instead. Circumflexes take the form of a horizontal stroke, sometimes with a diagonal upturn at the right-hand end, except when joined to nomina sacra strokes.
The sigma telikon is present. Beta takes a highly unusual form, like a long-bowed majuscule beta without its upper loop, resembling a curved Latin lower-case letter b.

Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, lower comma, question mark and full stop. The question mark appears in an unusual form, the dot being roughly level with the top of the curved mark and to its left, rather than directly above it (e.g f. 67r, lines 10-12, 14-15).

decoDesc.decoNote: Each Psalm or Ode begins with an enlarged initial in red ink, usually ornamented, somewhat crude and sometimes overlapping with the text. Verses begin with normal letters in red ink.

additions.p: From f. 9r onwards the number and Latin incipit of each Psalm has been written alongside its beginning, in red ink, by a late 15th-century hand. The same hand has added occasional interlinear Latin glosses (e.g. f. 9v).

There are notes added in the margins by Patrick Young, in Greek and Latin, in black ink, on ff. 1r-17r, giving collations with another manuscript and various editions, commentaries and catenae. Young has added a note on f. [i] verso, listing the abbreviations used for the various texts cited in these annotations. Another hand has added a note regarding a further manuscript beneath this list (Codex Ravii in Ps. 18), and written another note on this folio: In hoc codice absunt Psalmorum tituli universi.
The present classmark and the former classmarks No. 339, H.25 and O.10.29 have been marked on f. [ii] recto. The former classmark No. 1255 has been marked on f. 1r.

binding.p: Full leather binding over wooden boards, with plain pastedowns, bound by the "Scales binder" around 1470. The boards are decorated with blind tooling, using stamps and cutwork. Motifs including the fleur de lys, a crowned lion and a dolphin. As part of this design, the inscription Bhale was incised in the centre of the right board. There are two metal catches on the right board and corresponding sets of three pegs on the left board, surviving from fastenings whose clasps are now lost.
binding.condition: The binding has been rebacked. There is some damage to the lower outer corners of the boards, where some of the leather covering has been lost.

physDesc.accMat: The endleaves and pastedowns are of parchment.

history.origin: The copyist has been identified from the script as Manuel of Constantinople Manuel of Constantinople (RGK I 115, II 147; PLP 6030), who was active in the second half of the 15th century, producing a dated manuscript in 1468. The binding has been identified as the work of the "Scales binder", who worked in London, and dated by the tools in use to around 1470. This suggests that the manuscript was copied in the third quarter of the 15th century, most probably in the 1460s. It was probably copied in England, in the light of evidence from other manuscripts copied by Manuel for an English patron and in collaboration with a scribe known to have worked in England, his use here of leaf signatures, the presence of early Latin annotations by an apparently English hand, and the fact that this manuscript was bound in London at such an early date.

provenance.p: Probably owned around 1470 by a person named Bhale, as suggested by the text incised into the binding. It has been suggested that this could have been the Carmelite friar Robert Bale (d. 1503) Bale, Robert, d. 1503 (Barker, 'Scales Binder', p. 365).
Owned by the Biblical scholar and royal librarian Patrick Young (1584-1652) Young, Patrick, 1584-1652 .
Acquired after his death by the antiquary Thomas Gale (c. 1635-1702) Gale, Thomas, 1635?-1702 , Fellow of Trinity and Dean of York, along with many of Young's other manuscripts.

history.acquisition: Donated to Trinity College by Thomas's son, the antiquary Roger Gale (1672-1744) Gale, Roger, 1672-1744 , in 1738.
